{{Infobox protected area | name = Alaka{{okina}}i Wilderness Preserve | iucn_category = V | photo = Alakai_swamp.jpg | map = Hawaii | map_caption = State of Hawaii | location = [[Kauai]], [[Hawaii]], [[United States|USA]] | nearest_city = [[Waimea, Kauai County, Hawaii|Waimea, Hawaii]] | coordinates = {{coords|22|06|30|N|159|33|30|W|region:US|display=inline, title}} | area = {{convert|9000|acre|km2}} | established = 1981 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = Hawaii Division of Forestry and Wildlife }}
The '''Alaka{{okina}}i Wilderness Preserve''', popularly known as '''Alaka{{okina}}i Swamp''', is a [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests#Wet forests|montane wet forest]] on the [[Hawaii]]an island of [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i]]. Although the preserve is home to alpine [[Hawaiian tropical rainforests#Bogs|bogs]], it is not a true [[swamp]].<ref>{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426000642/http://www.nature.org/wherewework/northamerica/states/hawaii/projectprofiles/art27252.html |archive-date=April 26, 2009|dead-url=yes |url=http://www.nature.org/wherewework/northamerica/states/hawaii/projectprofiles/art27252.html |title=Alakaʻi Wilderness |work=The Nature Conservancy in Hawaiʻi |publisher=[[The Nature Conservancy]] |accessdate=2009-03-01}}</ref> It is located on a [[plateau]] near [[Mount Waialeale|Mount Wai{{okina}}ale{{okina}}ale]], one of the wettest spots on Earth.
The {{convert|3.5|mi|km|adj=on}} Alaka{{okina}}i Swamp trail is often shrouded in mist. This trail can be reached via the Pihea Vista trail, which is connected to the Pu{{okina}}u o Kila lookout on [[Waimea Canyon]] road. This road is located behind a gate that is directly next to the [[Kalalau Valley]] lookout. Due to the rainfall experienced here, potholes are formed and the road is often closed. The end of this trail overlooks [[Hanalei Bay]] off in the distance and it is possible to see several waterfalls from the lookout. This area is often shrouded in clouds and is one of the few places on Kaua{{okina}}i where one may walk through them.
