'''Edenderry Power Station''' is a large [[peat|peat-fired]] power station near [[Edenderry]], in the [[Republic of Ireland]]. The station is capable of generating up to {{nowrap|120 [[Megawatt|MWe]]}} of power,<ref>{{Citation |title=Edenderry Power - Plant Description |url=http://www.edenderrypower.ie/inside.asp?id=5 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216071754/http://www.edenderrypower.ie/inside.asp?id=5 |archivedate=2012-02-16 |df= }}</ref> making it the second-largest peat-fired power station in the country. It has been owned by [[Bord na Móna]] since 2006 and is part of the Powergen section of the Peat Energy Division. It was purchased from [[E.ON]] in December 2005. Trials of co-fuelling the plant with biomass commenced in 2007 and were successful. Currently the plant is co-fired with about 9% biomass, with a target of 30% co-fuelling<ref>{{Citation|title=Edenderry Power - Bio-Mass|url=http://www.edenderrypower.ie/inside.asp?id=4}}</ref> by 2015.

