{{refimprove|date=September 2016}}

'''Orbit@home''' was a [[Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing|BOINC]]-based [[distributed computing]] project of the [[Planetary Science Institute]].  It uses the "[[orbit (astronomy and physics)|Orbit]] Reconstruction, [[Simulation]] and Analysis"<ref>[http://orsa.sourceforge.net/index.html ORSA - Orbit Reconstruction, Simulation and Analysis]. Retrieved on 2011-02-20.</ref> framework to optimize the search strategies that are used to find [[near-Earth object]]s.

On March 4, 2008, Orbit@home completed the installation of its new [[server (computing)|server]] and officially opened to new members. On April 11, Orbit@home launched a [[Windows (operating system)|Windows]] version of their [[client (computing)|client]]. On February 16, 2013, the project was halted due to lack of [[grant (money)|grant funding]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orbit.psi.edu/?q=node/32 |title=orbit@home is upgrading! |publisher=Orbit.psi.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-29}}</ref> However, on July 23, 2013, the Orbit@home project was selected for funding by [[NASA]]'s [[Near Earth Object]] Observation program.  It was announced that Orbit@home is to resume operations sometime in 2014 or 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orbit.psi.edu/?q=node/33 |title=orbit@home is upgrading! |publisher=Orbit.psi.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-07-06}}</ref> As of July 13, 2018, Orbit@home is offline according to its website, and the upgrade announcement has been removed.

